{"author":"Joe Oakhart","author_email":"joeoakhart+bot@navapbc.com","author_id":"594c-9dcf-5ad6-4e6d","data":{"fields":{"description":"# v1.0 release-readiness hardening\n\nClose the five validated readiness findings for `navapbc/rebar` before the v1.0\nrelease, using well-established patterns from actively-maintained OSS projects\n(uv, pydantic, pip for release integrity; git repository-format-version for the\nstore compatibility gate; nginx/OpenSSH for removed-input tombstones). Every\nfinding was independently verified against current `main` (see per-story\nprovenance); all five are valid.\n\n## Context\n\nrebar dogfoods a Gerrit-gated `main` (two independent votes: `LLM-Review` +\n`Verified`) with GitHub as a read-only mirror, yet the **release and\nstore-compatibility surfaces sit outside that trust boundary**. The five findings\nare independent but share one theme: a control that exists at the code-review\nboundary is missing at the release / storage / configuration boundary.\n\n- **Finding 1** — `release.yml` publishes on any human-pushed `v*` tag with no\n  machine proof the tagged SHA is the reviewed-and-landed `main`; tags were\n  deliberately left unprotected (`infra/terraform-github/main.tf:23-28`).\n- **Finding 2** — there is no committed store-format-version / required-capability\n  record, so a future release cannot make an already-installed v1.0 binary\n  fail-closed on a store it cannot correctly interpret. This gate **must ship in\n  v1.0 itself** — a v1.0 binary cannot retroactively learn to inspect a record\n  whose semantics did not exist in v1.0. This is the most time-critical story.\n  **Legacy-store (absent-record) policy is load-bearing:** every store created by\n  a pre-v1.0 build has no record, so the gate must treat *absent* as the implicit\n  legacy format (version 0, compatible / fail-**open**) and let the idempotent\n  ensure-registry write the record on the next covered write — fail-**closed** only\n  when the record is *present but incompatible*. Absent-means-blocked would break\n  upgrade-in-place for every existing user; absent-means-silently-bypassed would\n  defeat the gate. The expand-contract path and a safe rollback story are part of\n  the child (see Finding 2's story).\n- **Finding 3** — `python -m build`'s default wheel-from-sdist path bakes\n  `COMMIT = None` into the published wheel, and CI installs the source tree\n  (`pip install .`) rather than the artifact bundle, so the defect is uncaught\n  until after PyPI immutability sets in.\n- **Finding 4** — the release pipeline resolves actions, build tools, and a\n  privileged OIDC-context binary from mutable references; the repo already\n  SHA-pins actions in `gerrit-verify.yaml`, so `release.yml` is inconsistent with\n  its own stricter convention.\n- **Finding 5** — removed env vars are silently ignored and removed TOML keys get\n  only a generic \"typo?\" warning, including surfaces that redirect the store\n  (`TICKETS_TRACKER_DIR`), toggle write gates (`REBAR_MCP_ALLOW_RECONCILE_LIVE`),\n  and change close policy (`verify.require_verdict_for_close`).\n\n**Sequencing (encoded as dependency links).** Finding 2 first (must land in v1.0 to\nbe effective at all). Findings 1, 3, 4 all edit `release.yml`; they are serialised\nby `depends_on` links in the order 4 → 3 → 1 (pin the toolchain, then restructure\nbuild-once, then add the source-authorization gate) — so the Gerrit queue cannot\nprocess them out of order — and file-impact is recorded so `next-batch` also\nserialises them. Finding 5 is independent and can proceed in parallel; Finding 2 is\nindependent (highest priority). `docs/releasing.md` is edited by all three release\nstories, so section ownership is assigned per-story (pinning → Finding 4;\nbuild-once → Finding 3; authorization → Finding 1) to avoid overlap.\n\n## Success Criteria\n\n- A `v*` tag can only publish artifacts when its commit is reachable from\n  reviewed-and-landed `main` and the tag/pyproject/server.json versions agree\n  exactly, with production publication gated behind an independently-approved\n  environment.\n- A v1.0 binary reads a committed store compatibility record and fails closed\n  (reads/diagnostics still allowed) on a **present-but-incompatible** record —\n  unknown format version or unrecognised required capability — before any mutate /\n  compact / push / reconcile side effect; an **absent** record (every pre-v1.0\n  store) is treated as the legacy format (version 0, compatible), and the idempotent\n  ensure-registry writes the record on the next covered write, so upgrade-in-place\n  works with no manual step; optional additive events keep today's preserve-and-ignore\n  behaviour, and a rollback to a pre-v1.0 binary leaves the store operable (the\n  record is an ignored-unknown file to old binaries).\n- The exact wheel and sdist are installed and exercised before publication, the\n  bytes tested are the bytes published (hash-verified), and the shipped wheel\n  carries the correct non-null source commit.\n- Every executable the release depends on is identified by an immutable reference\n  (full action SHAs, a hash-locked build environment, an exact-versioned +\n  digest-verified MCP publisher) and checkouts do not persist credentials.\n- Removed inputs that affect store location, write/sync gates, auth, security, or\n  lifecycle policy fail loud with a targeted migration message and a nonzero exit;\n  genuinely unknown keys keep the project's chosen forward-compatibility policy.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] All five child stories are closed.\n- [ ] Each child story's change has landed on `main` through the Gerrit\n  two-vote gate (`LLM-Review +1` AND `Verified +1`).\n- [ ] The store-compatibility gate (Finding 2) is present in the tree that ships\n  as v1.0 (verified by the reader existing and being wired into the write paths),\n  since it cannot be added retroactively.\n- [ ] The Finding 2 story defines and documents the absent-record (pre-v1.0 store)\n  policy — absent = legacy/compatible, record auto-written by the ensure-registry on\n  next covered write, fail-closed only when present-but-incompatible — and a\n  rollback-safe outcome for a pre-v1.0 binary encountering the record.\n- [ ] `docs/releasing.md` and `docs/migrations.md` are updated to describe the new\n  release-authorization gate, the build-once artifact flow, and the store\n  compatibility record (including the absent-record upgrade/rollback path).\n- [ ] Each child story's plan-review advisory findings are recorded with an explicit\n  Accept/Reject disposition and a one-line rationale (as a comment on the child\n  ticket), and every Accepted finding is reflected in the child's description before\n  that child's change receives its Gerrit `LLM-Review +1` / `Verified +1` votes."}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1784045835308151001,"uuid":"a78b0594-c94d-4514-8f43-7359883f1127"}